Curt Sampson wrote:

&gt; 
&gt;     public void myPublicMethod()
&gt;     {
&gt;       // no problem mocking the HTTP Servlet Reqest
&gt;       params = readParamsFromHttpServletRequest();
&gt;       myPrivateMethod(params);
&gt; 
&gt;       // How do I mock either &#39;client&#39; or &#39;ServiceLocator&#39;
&gt;       OrgMgrServiceClient client = getOrgMgrServiceClient();
&gt;       client.doStuff();
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt;     private OrgMgrServiceClient _client;
&gt; 
&gt;     private OrgMgrServiceClient getOrgMgrServiceClient() {
&gt;       if (_client != null)
&gt;           return _client;
&gt;       else
&gt;           return ServiceLocator.getOrgMgrServiceClient();
&gt;     }
&gt; 
&gt;     void setOrgMgrServiceClient(OrgMgrServiceClient client) {
&gt;       _client = client;
&gt;     }

That&#39;s a standard pattern: setter injection. /Now/ you can mock easily. 
I had thought that you weren&#39;t allowed to change that class at all -- 
but if you were able to add methods to it, that changes everything.

Good job.
